The Plague Mandate was Shadowmere's emergency legal regime that expanded containment powers without reliable sunset controls.
It was issued jointly by Midgaard's Crown and regional lords during blight-fever and battlefield contagion outbreaks in the frontier march.
The Mandate gave Shadowmere's command structure authority to: impose rapid intake without lineage review, enforce forced quarantines, order immediate cremation without appeal, and temporarily suspend lineage-inheritance claims.
Each power was justified by a specific crisis need: rapid intake managed volume, forced quarantine contained spread, immediate cremation prevented reanimation, suspension of lineage claims cleared administrative backlogs.
Temporary was written into the Mandate's language. The definition of temporary was not written in.
When plague peaks receded, no authority agreed on what rollback looked like or who had standing to declare it completed.
Crown envoys demanded restored noble precedence; Compact wardens insisted containment powers remain; temple delegates sought release rites for mass graves; march commanders refused to relinquish emergency command chains.
The Mandate's powers did not expire; they calcified into permanent institutional function embedded in Shadowmere's administration.
The processing halls, poison works, deep binding cells, and intake trenches built during the Mandate period became permanent architecture rather than crisis infrastructure.
Shadowmere's legal identity in current governance is the Plague Mandate period's unresolved administrative state: a frontier march still operating under emergency powers that no authority has successfully rolled back.
The most enduring institutional product of the Mandate is the Binder Collegium, whose record-soul classification practices were originally Mandate-period intake procedures.

