---
Rakuen's Garden Ledger treats the Plague Mandate as the foundational document for understanding what disaster-recovery protocols must prevent.
The Mandate responded to a genuine crisis efficiently. When the crisis ended, the processing infrastructure had no transition to peacetime function. It continued operating. Infrastructure with no peacetime function must be decommissioned when the crisis ends; the Mandate's was not. Shadowmere is the result.
Rakuen's drawdown protocols specify this transition: when crisis metrics fall below threshold, crisis infrastructure begins managed decommission or repurposing.
Post-crisis assessment reviews infrastructure purpose: does this serve the recovery, or does it serve the crisis that is now over?
This rule has been applied fourteen times. It has produced no Shadowmere outcomes. Rakuen considers this evidence that the rule works.

