---
Ashborn communities near Shadowmere's frontier zone were directly affected by the Plague Mandate's suspension of lineage-inheritance claims, applied without distinction between community types.
Plague clearance required documentation that Ashborn communities, which did not use Midgaard's standard documentary practices, could not easily produce.
The suspension lasted longer for Ashborn communities; the clearance pathway was not designed for non-standard documentation practices.
This asymmetric burden was not intentional but was not corrected when the disparity became apparent. Equal application of emergency powers to communities with unequal compliance access is not equal treatment.
Ashborn communities named this problem to intake officers; the officers forwarded complaints through channels leading to the same administrators who had applied the powers.
The Mandate's complaint mechanism was not independent of its administration. The lesson persists in Ashborn engagement with Midgaard's administrative systems.
